data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which combines the type check and fails with a clear message if wrong:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", ((EmailHandler)result).Type);
}
```

The cast-then-null-check approach silently passes if the cast returns `null` (which won't happen with `(EmailHandler)` — that throws). `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` makes the intent explicit and gives a descriptive failure message like *"Expected type: EmailHandler, Actual type: SmsHandler"*.

If you need the typed reference for further assertions, you can also use the generic overload that returns the cast value (MSTest v3+):

```csharp
var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
```
